{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:34:59.434Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing the Upgrade**\n\nI've made good progress! The styling of the new ROI Calculator aligns seamlessly with the `ToolPageShell`, complete with clear premium indicators. My next step is to nail down the necessary inputs for the upgraded calculator, so I'm drafting an internal design plan to organize my thoughts.\n\n\n**Conceptualizing the Interface**\n\nI'm now deep in the design phase, and it feels promising. I'm moving toward an \"executive console\" aesthetic for the ROI calculator's user interface. I'm focusing on an interactive \"Sovereign Financial Cockpit\" visual metaphor, so the input form will be styled in a premium, executive console layout on the left, using a grid.\n\n\n**Refining the Visualization**\n\nI'm now integrating sliders and segmented controls into the design for a more intuitive input experience. I'm also planning an interactive side preview, a dynamic dashboard that updates as users edit fields, showing KPIs alongside the \"Sovereign Financial Value Waterfall Chart.\" I will ensure formulas accurately connect inputs to outputs. I have also designed a layout strategy for a two-column grid on desktop and a single column on mobile. Inputs will be organized under collapsible tabs, and the side preview will display clear KPIs and a strategic narrative.\n\n\n**Defining Interactive Elements**\n\nI'm now focusing on interactive elements, so I've finalized custom sliders with micro-interactions and segmented controls, with safe numerical input validation and real-time feedback. I'm also including a \"Copy Markdown Report\" option that captures all inputs and outputs. Outputs will be clearly marked as illustrative/modelled.\n\n**Prioritizing Mobile Adaptability**\n\nI am thinking about mobile design, and I've focused on responsive layout. Inputs stack on small screens, sliders have large touch targets, and charts adapt dynamically.\n\n\n**Specifying the Inputs**\n\nI've been working on defining the specific user inputs for the ROI calculator. I've broken down all the key fields. I'm focusing on providing users with a selection of enterprise industries, company sizes, and functions, using dropdowns or segmented controls. I am defining numerical inputs like annual cost baseline, process volume, and average handling time. I've also added sliders for automation target percentage and segmented controls for current manual effort level.\n\n\n**Defining Key Inputs**\n\nI'm now focusing on specific inputs and how they fit into the ROI model. I've designed a slider for the `expectedProductivityImprovementRange`, allowing for a percentage range with visual feedback. The `implementationHorizon` will be a segmented control for ease of use. I'm also now modeling ROI with a calculation for wasted costs based on the baseline cost and manual effort level, with Low manual effort as 15% of cost.\n\n\n**Calculating the Savings**\n\nI'm now calculating manual overhead costs using an `annualCostBaseline` and `manualEffortFactor`. I'll also estimate annual manual hours if an `averageHandlingTime` is given, or I will use an estimated hourly rate. I am also modeling the actual savings achieved with automation using the `automationTargetPercentage` and the improvement in `productivityImprovement`. Finally, I'm modeling expected, conservative, and aggressive gross savings.\n\n\n**Modeling the Savings**\n\nI'm now calculating conservative and aggressive savings. I'm modelling the reclaimed hours, using different formulas depending on whether we have handling time data or not. Next, I'll integrate the initial investment calculation, which depends on company size and implementation timeline, with a custom input. I'll need to figure out which user inputs are necessary.\n\n\n**Determining the CapEx**\n\nI'm now determining how to handle the initial investment. I've decided to create an \"Estimated GFF Platform CapEx\" field that pre-populates based on the selected company size, but can be overridden by the user. I've designed specific pre-population values for different company sizes. I am also making sure that the outputs are accurate, and not placeholders, so they feel like a real calculation. I will model the Expected Net Savings and Expected ROI calculations now, as well.\n\n\n\n"}}
