{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:40.573Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing Input Interaction**\n\nI'm now focused on the \"Expected Productivity Improvement\" input. I've scrapped the initial idea for a custom slider and have decided on a single slider labeled \"Target Productivity Boost\" with a dynamic range, offering a clean, user-friendly interface. This will give users flexibility and still provide executive-friendly options for target selection. I'm also looking at the \"Deployment & Adoption Horizon\" options: \"3 Months (Fast Track)\", \"6 Months (Standard)\", and \"12 Months (Strategic)\".\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:41.767Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Modeling ROI Formula**\n\nI'm now deep in thought about the underlying math for the `/build/roi` upgrade. I want to build a frontend-only model. I'm focusing on ensuring it's bulletproof, dynamic, and produces flawless outputs. I'm prioritizing edge case handling, especially avoiding negatives, NaNs, and infinities. I am finalizing the formula.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:43.769Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Calculating Wage/Cost Structure**\n\nI'm now determining how to calculate labor costs for the ROI model. I've designed a wage calculation matrix based on industry and function multipliers to assign an hourly wage for accurate ROI projections. The next step is validating this for accuracy. The goal is to provide a realistic base rate.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:45.327Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Calculating Labor Costs**\n\nI've crafted a method to calculate the loaded hourly rate based on industry and function multipliers. This is a game-changer! I've also just defined how to estimate the annual manual effort cost, representing a portion of the baseline budget spent on manual tasks, leveraging a manual effort factor (low, medium, high, critical) to determine addressable costs. I am also working on how to calculate Annual Hours Spent.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:47.681Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Adjusting CapEx Parameters**\n\nI'm now focusing on calculating capital expenditure (CapEx) based on the implementation horizon. I've designed adjustments for different timelines, accounting for resource allocation. Shorter horizons will incur higher costs due to rapid deployment, while longer horizons will spread the investment. I have also decided that I want to keep custom Initial Investment synchronized, and editable with a slider. I'm focusing on the auto-update to keep this intuitive for the user.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:48.985Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Savings Calculations**\n\nI've just refined the savings calculations for the ROI model! It feels very clean and intuitive now. The equations for `expectedSavingsFactor`, `conservativeSavingsFactor`, and `aggressiveSavingsFactor` are now perfectly clear, and linked to the underlying slider values. I've built in cases for a more conservative estimate of savings (reflecting lower adoption and productivity), and a more aggressive case (for hyper-adoption and synergistic benefits). This will ensure the model is flexible for different needs.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:50.245Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Calculating ROI Projections**\n\nI'm now determining key calculations for ROI scenarios. I'm focused on `aggressiveGrossSavings` and `aggressiveHoursSaved`. I'm also now calculating the net savings and ROI percentages, and payback periods for both conservative and expected models, ensuring all scenarios handle potential edge cases gracefully, such as zero initial investments. I've built in calculations to limit negative numbers, and ensure that both outputs are realistic.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:52.212Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Validating Math Model**\n\nI'm now implementing thorough validation checks for the ROI model. I've focused on graceful handling of edge cases, particularly when the initial investment is zero, ensuring outputs are realistic and preventing errors. I've also incorporated input capping to avoid negative or NaN values for key parameters like baseline costs, process volume, average handling time, and initial investment. I'm reviewing the implementation to identify any gaps.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T19:35:53.856Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Revisiting Strategic Priorities**\n\nI'm now integrating the strategic priority toggle back into the ROI upgrade. I'll make sure it's fully implemented to influence calculations and descriptions, keeping the original landing page design intact. I'm also reviewing how the `priority` affects the existing markdown report for alignment. It's fantastic to preserve this, while adding more structure. I'm now examining the input panel structure.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
